<p>
	A Happy Number is a number when you sum the square of its digits, and repeat, you eventually get one.
<p>
<p>Take, for example, the number 19:</p>
<ul>
	<li>1<sup>2</sup> + 9<sup>2</sup> = 82</li>
	<li>8<sup>2</sup> + 2<sup>2</sup> = 68</li>
	<li>6<sup>2</sup> + 8<sup>2</sup> = 100</li>
	<li>1<sup>2</sup> + 0<sup>2</sup> + 0<sup>2</sup> = 1</li>
</ul>
<p>We reached zero, so 19 is happy.</p>
<p>Now, take the number 14:</p>
<ul>
	<li>1<sup>2</sup> + 4<sup>2</sup> = 17</li>
	<li>1<sup>2</sup> + 7<sup>2</sup> = 50</li>
	<li>5<sup>2</sup> + 0<sup>2</sup> = 25</li>
	<li>2<sup>2</sup> + 5<sup>2</sup> = 29</li>
	<li>2<sup>2</sup> + 9<sup>2</sup> = 85</li>
	<li>8<sup>2</sup> + 5<sup>2</sup> = 89</li>
	<li>8<sup>2</sup> + 9<sup>2</sup> = 145</li>
	<li>1<sup>2</sup> + 4<sup>2</sup> + 5<sup>2</sup> = 42</li>
	<li>4<sup>2</sup> + 2<sup>2</sup> = 20</li>
</ul>
<p>And so on. With a few more steps, we reach a number that we've seen before and thus know we will never make it to one.</p>
<p>Create a solution that, given a positive integer n, states whether n is happy or not.</p>